comment.narrative:
1. Existence of RRG including I-PDNA, yet assessment tool to address the early recovery needs;

2. A pilot disaster impact information systems that can support recovery planning, assessment, and monitoring processes introduced in 2011 for the Merapi Volcano eruption recovery;

3. A model of post-disaster recovery monitoring framework involving active community participation – the Longitudinal Study - introduced in 2011 for the Merapi Volcano eruption recovery, and being adopted in 2012 to be managed by GoI;
4. Lesson learned in developing Indonesia PDNA is documented in 2011.
5. Pilot for monitoring the impact of recovery has been undertaken in Merapi (LS & DRI), but requires further testing and refinement of the instruments and to gain acknowledgement by govt. 
6. Knowledge products on PDNA, HRNA, ERNA, VIS, Asmaradana, and Dancing Leaves, have been produced and disseminated nationally, as well as shared at regional level (Myanmar & Laos)

1. 5 coordination meetings undertaken at district & provincial level in the areas of RENAKSI, RR implementation and RR M&E

2. Process of developing PDNAs for Mount Sinabung eruptions is supported and accomplished in Q1 2015;

3. Process of developing RENAKSIs for  Sinabung Volcanic Eruption are supported and accomplished in Q2 2015;

4. Recommendations proposed & issues identified for sector-based RR implementation;

5. Periodic reassessment of needs and progress of disaster recovery undertaken (field testing LS & social audit)

6. DM plans developed for 1 district affected by Sinabung eruption

7. 32 contingency plans developed in collaboration with village & district govt 

8. VIS and Sister-Village database developed for 25 villages affected by Mt. Sinabung eruption

1). Village level conflict-sensitive budgeting developed and disseminated.

2) National adoption of conflict prevention curriculum for government apparatus (end user);

3) Conflict vulnerability index in Indonesia disseminated and applied as tool for early warning and early response mechanism.

